AC"><i>Scientific Method in Practice</i></a> (Reprint ed.). Cambridge University Press. p.&#160;3. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780521017084" title="Special:BookSources/9780521017084">9780521017084</a>. <q>The scientific method \'is often misrepresented as a fixed sequence of steps,\' rather than being seen for what it truly is, \'a highly variable and creative process\' (AAAS 2000:18). The claim here is that science has general principles that must be mastered to increase productivity and enhance perspective, not that these principles provide a simple and automated sequence of steps to follow.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AScientific+method&amp;rft.aufirst=Hugh+G.&amp;rft.aulast=Gauch&amp;rft.btitle=Scientific+Method+in+Practice&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.edition=Reprint&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=9780521017084&amp;rft.pages=3&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2F%3Fid%3DiVkugqNG9dAC&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Inductive_Science_1837-11"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Inductive_Science_1837_11-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Inductive_Science_1837_11-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><i>History of Inductive Science</i> (1837), and in <i>Philosophy of Inductive Science</i> (1840)</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-12"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web">Smolin, Lee. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://bigthink.com/in-their-own-words/there-is-no-scientific-method">"There is No Scientific Method"</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span c